<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="250" pageId="15" pageNumber="248" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[805,1493,1962,2115]" lastBlockId="16.[57,746,1834,2115]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="249" pageId="15" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis box="[805,868,1962,1986]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="248">Notes</emphasis>
: Among the hydnoid fungi associated with 
<taxonomicName box="[1327,1486,1962,1986]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="15" pageNumber="248" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sylvestris">
<emphasis box="[1327,1486,1962,1986]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="248">Pinus sylvestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nitare &amp; Ainsworth &amp; Larsson &amp; Parfitt &amp; Suz &amp; Svantesson &amp; Larsson" authorityYear="2021" box="[805,1099,1994,2018]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Bankeraceae" genus="Hydnellum" kingdom="Fungi" order="Thelephorales" pageId="15" pageNumber="248" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="roseoviolaceum">
<emphasis box="[805,1099,1994,2018]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="248">Hydnellum roseoviolaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be very close to, and has been mistaken for, 
<taxonomicName box="[1013,1247,2026,2050]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Bankeraceae" genus="Hydnellum" kingdom="Fungi" order="Thelephorales" pageId="15" pageNumber="248" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="fuligineoviolaceum">
<emphasis box="[1013,1247,2026,2050]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="248">H. fuligineoviolaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to its tendency to assume a lilac flesh.It differs by smaller spores,colour changes in the flesh from rose to violet (not being violet from the beginning as in 
<taxonomicName box="[111,344,1834,1858]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Bankeraceae" genus="Hydnellum" kingdom="Fungi" order="Thelephorales" pageId="16" pageNumber="249" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="fuligineoviolaceum">
<emphasis box="[111,344,1834,1858]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="249">H. fuligineoviolaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and its mild taste (
<emphasis box="[555,600,1834,1858]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="249">N.B.</emphasis>
some people cannot detect the very acrid taste of 
<taxonomicName box="[471,706,1866,1890]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Bankeraceae" genus="Hydnellum" kingdom="Fungi" order="Thelephorales" pageId="16" pageNumber="249" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="fuligineoviolaceum">
<emphasis box="[471,706,1866,1890]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="249">H. fuligineoviolaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). It differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[188,327,1898,1923]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Bankeraceae" genus="Hydnellum" kingdom="Fungi" order="Thelephorales" pageId="16" pageNumber="249" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="glaucopus">
<emphasis box="[188,205,1898,1922]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[217,373,1898,1922]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="249">glaucopus e.g.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its more intense rose-lilac flesh and by being associated with 
<taxonomicName box="[388,446,1930,1954]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="16" pageNumber="249" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
