<paragraph blockId="17.[57,746,1290,1826]" pageId="17" pageNumber="250">
An ITS BLAST search in GenBank brings up two western North American sequences as the closest matches at 95–96 %. These sequences are both generated from ectomycorrhizal root-tips, one from a 
<taxonomicName box="[181,342,1578,1602]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="17" pageNumber="250" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="muricata">
<emphasis box="[181,342,1578,1602]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="250">Pinus muricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
stand in northern California (
<bibRefCitation author="Moeller HV &amp; Peay KG &amp; Fukami T" journalOrPublisher="FEMS Microbiology Ecology" pageId="17" pageNumber="250" pagination="797 - 806" part="87" refId="ref16307" refString="Moeller HV, Peay KG, Fukami T (2014). Ectomycorrhizal fungal traits reflect environmental conditions along a coastal California edaphic gradient. FEMS Microbiology Ecology 87: 797 - 806." title="Ectomycorrhizal fungal traits reflect environmental conditions along a coastal California edaphic gradient" type="journal article" year="2014">
Moeller 
<emphasis box="[57,109,1610,1634]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="250">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
), the other from 
<taxonomicName box="[386,635,1610,1634]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pseudotsuga" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="17" pageNumber="250" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="menziesii">
<emphasis box="[386,635,1610,1634]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="250">Pseudotsuga menziesii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in British Columbia (
<bibRefCitation author="Kranabetter JM &amp; Stoehr M &amp; O'Neill GA" box="[177,449,1642,1667]" journalOrPublisher="New Phytologist" pageId="17" pageNumber="250" pagination="1135 - 1144" part="206" refId="ref15843" refString="Kranabetter JM, Stoehr M, O'Neill GA (2015). Ectomycorrhizal fungal maladaptation and growth reductions associated with assisted migration of Douglas-fir. New Phytologist 206: 1135 - 1144." title="Ectomycorrhizal fungal maladaptation and growth reductions associated with assisted migration of Douglas-fir" type="journal article" year="2015">
Kranabetter 
<emphasis box="[318,371,1642,1666]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="250">et al</emphasis>
. 2015
</bibRefCitation>
). The sequence difference to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nitare &amp; Ainsworth &amp; Larsson &amp; Parfitt &amp; Suz &amp; Svantesson &amp; Larsson" authorityYear="2021" box="[91,296,1674,1698]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Bankeraceae" genus="Hydnellum" kingdom="Fungi" order="Thelephorales" pageId="17" pageNumber="250" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="roseoviolaceum">
<emphasis box="[91,296,1674,1698]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="250">H. roseoviolaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
consists of 15 indels and 14 gaps. We currently cannot suggest any name for this American sister taxon, if any exists. If the basidiomatal colours are like those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nitare &amp; Ainsworth &amp; Larsson &amp; Parfitt &amp; Suz &amp; Svantesson &amp; Larsson" authorityYear="2021" box="[87,288,1770,1794]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Bankeraceae" genus="Hydnellum" kingdom="Fungi" order="Thelephorales" pageId="17" pageNumber="250" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="roseoviolaceum">
<emphasis box="[87,288,1770,1794]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="250">H. roseoviolaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is likely to become misidentified as 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Bankeraceae" genus="Hydnellum" kingdom="Fungi" order="Thelephorales" pageId="17" pageNumber="250" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="fuscoindicum">
<emphasis box="[721,738,1770,1794]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="250">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[57,207,1802,1826]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="250">fuscoindicum.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
